node.text:
Two website providers have dealt a significant blow to an anti-abortion organization that tried to establish a 'bounty hunting' online form to allow private citizens to report individuals and reproductive health care centers helping pregnant people get an abortion in Texas. ⁠
⁠
Texas' anti-abortion law, S.B. 8, prohibits abortions after just 6 weeks, even in cases of rape and incest, and also gives citizens—even complete strangers—the right to sue anyone who is deemed to have assisted in performing an abortion, from doctors to potentially even Uber drivers.⁠
⁠
Texas Right to Life's website, ProLifeWhistleblower.com, has gone dark twice after domain hosting companies GoDaddy and Epik said the site violated their terms of service. In a statement to CBS News, a GoDaddy spokesperson said the site 'violated multiple provisions, including but not limited to, Section 5.2 of our terms of service,' which says customers cannot 'collect or harvest' private information or 'personally identifiable information' about an individual or entity without their consent.⁠
⁠
The other provider, Epik—which never hosted the website but acted as its registrar—said it would refuse to do business with Texas Right to Life if it continued to collect people's private information, according to the Washington Post. As of September 8, ProLifeWhistleblower.com redirects to the Texas Right to Life website. A spokesperson for the organization says it's looking for another domain host.⁠
⁠
Pro-abortion supporters and activists had also been busy disrupting ProLifeWhistleblower.com's online snitching systems when it was initially set up, reportedly flooding the website with spam and fake messages.⁠
⁠
Meanwhile, Reddit has also taken similar actions against anti-abortion snitching on its platform by shutting down a subreddit, r/TXBountyHunters, that was formed on September 2 with similar intent in mind.⁠
⁠
⁠
#texas #abortion #reproductiverights #reddit

node.text:
The top 1% fails to pay up to $163 billion in taxes annually, according to a new report from the Treasury Department titled ‘The Case for a Robust Attack on the Tax Gap.’⁠
⁠
The report, authored by Deputy Assistant Secretary for Economic Policy Natasha Sarin, points to years of funding cuts to the Internal Revenue Service as part of the problem. ‘An under-staffed IRS, with outdated technology, is unable to collect 15 percent of taxes that are owed,’ the report says.⁠
⁠
The report applauds the Biden administration’s calls to approve more funding for the IRS, saying that an overhaul of the agency and investment in staffing could net ‘an estimated $1.6 trillion in additional tax revenue’ over the course of a decade.⁠
⁠
⁠

In a unanimous decision, the Supreme Court of Mexico voted to decriminalize abortion on September 7, another massive decision for reproductive rights in heavily Catholic Latin America. Only four countries in that region—Argentina, Cuba, Uruguay, and Guyana— allow for generally unrestrained access to abortion.⁠
⁠
Abortion had already been legalized in 4 of Mexico's 32 federal entities. The court's decision does not automatically legalize the procedure nationwide in Mexico, but it does create a clear pathway for other states to legalize it in the days ahead. Women in Mexico who have previously been jailed for seeking an abortion will also reportedly be freed as a result of this ruling.⁠
⁠
'This will not only have an impact in Mexico; it will set the agenda for the entire Latin American region,' Melissa Ayala of the feminist organization GIRE told the Washington Post on Tuesday.⁠
⁠
⁠

node.text:
Texas Gov. Greg Abbott (R) signed the state’s newest voting restrictions into law on Tuesday. Among other measures, Texas S.B. 1 bans 24-hour voting locations and drive-thru voting; it also institutes new voter ID requirements for casting ballots by mail. Critics of the bill say that the introduction of expanded protections for partisan poll watchers could foment voter intimidation.⁠
⁠
Abbott called two special legislative sessions this summer to pass the Republican-backed bill. The first attempt to pass this bill—and other conservative agenda items—was foiled when dozens of Texas Democratic lawmakers fled the state for Washington, D.C., to press federal lawmakers to pass voting rights protections on the federal level. The bill eventually passed in the second special session later this summer. ⁠
⁠
⁠
